# Future Roadmap Considerations  
(Use these when designing or refactoring code paths)

## 1. Identity & Access (Upcoming Direction)
- Prefer **JWT-based identity** over any vendor-supplied identifiers.  
- Always design with **multi-IDP support in mind**.
- Do not assume static vendor identity — long term, identities may expire, rotate, or inherit enterprise hierarchy.

## 2. Vendor Experience Enhancements
- Vendor Portal will transform into a **real-time interface** with auto-refresh and live readiness updates.  

## 3. Contracts & Versions
- Canonical contract is always the **primary root**; vendor overrides are optional.  
- Long-term design should allow:
  - Contract version negotiation  
  - Multi-version coexistence  
  - Auto-migration support  
- Never assume “v1 only”; new work should allow versioning without breaking changes.

## 4. Mappings & Transformations
- Canonical pass-through should remain the default; transformations optional.  
- Future features may include:
  - Mapping templates or generators  
  - AI-assisted mapping suggestions  
  - Pre-compiled/high-performance mapping execution  
- Avoid designing brittle mapping loaders — keep them extensible.

## 5. Allowlist Access Logic
- Outbound/inbound separation remains an invariant.  
- Wildcard behavior should remain explicit and predictable.  
- Admin override will always be the highest authority; vendor cannot bypass gating.  
- Expect more granular rules later (operation groups, conditional flows, throttling).

## 6. Runtime & Execution Model
- Runtime API will eventually support:
  - Async flows  
  - Multi-hop vendor → hub → vendor chains  
  - Optional retries & dead-letter queues  
- Prefer designs that allow injecting alternative execution backends.  
- Avoid tight coupling between runtime execution and UI behavior.

## 7. AI Formatter & Bedrock Evolution
- Formatter must remain pluggable (Bedrock today, future providers later).  
- Avoid hardcoding model IDs, provider names, or capabilities.  
- Expect later support for:
  - AI enrichment  
  - Normalization  
  - Summaries for audit and compliance  
- Design pathways so AI is **optional**, not required.

## 8. Observability & Governance
- Future roadmap includes:
  - Full audit timeline per transaction  
  - Vendor-facing performance analytics  
  - Usage metering tied to vendor identity  
- Avoid patterns where metrics are embedded across code; prefer centralized logging utilities.

## 9. Scalability & Partitioning
- Vendor isolation must remain strong; future sharding strategies may divide vendors by region or tier.  
- Avoid code that assumes a single database or single region.  
- All new features should be region-agnostic.

## 10. Feature Flags / Gates
- All new features should be shipped behind **feature gates**.  
- Gates must always be **DB-driven** and **editable by Admin**, not code constants.  
- Avoid wiring new features directly into UI without gating capability.
---

Use this rule as “soft guidance” when Cursor assists with new features.  
New rules can be added freely — this file is intentionally lightweight and future-compatible.
